<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="432" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1436,151,1508]" pageId="31" pageNumber="432">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,333,1448,1472]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="432" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[835,941,1449,1472]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="432">truncatus</emphasis>
(= truncate) and the Latin 
<emphasis box="[1239,1328,1448,1472]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="432">apicalis</emphasis>
(= apex), referring to the obliquely truncate apex of the valva in the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
